{"title_page": "Life Insurance Corporation", "text_new": "{{short description|Largest insurance\n company in World}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Life Insurance Corporation\n| logo                = LIC Logo.svg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| logo_caption        = ''Yogakshemam Vahamyaham ''\n| type                = [[Government-owned corporation|Statutory Corporation]] established by an <br> [[Act of Parliament]]- <br>LIC Act 1956<br />\n| key_people          = M R Kumar (Chairman) T C Suseel kumar (Managing Director) vipin Anand (Managing Director) Mukesh Gupta (Managing Director) Rajkumar (Managing Director)\n| industry            = Financial services\n| products            = {{unbulleted list |[[Life insurance]], |[[health insurance]], |[[Investment management]],|[[Banking]],|[[Mutual fund]]}}\n| revenue             = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|337000|c}}\n(2019)\n| operating_income    = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|32241|c}}\n| net_income          = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|29956|c}}\n(2019)\n| assets              = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|3111847|c}}(2019)\n| equity              = \n| owner               = '''[[Government of India]]''' (100%)\n| num_employees       = 111,979 (Mar 2019)<ref name=\"licindia.in\">https://www.licindia.in/getattachment/Bottom-Links/annual-report/LIC-Annual-Report-2015-16.pdf.aspx</ref>\n| subsid              = {{Unbulleted list|[[LIC Housing Finance]]|LIC International Ltd|LIC Cards Services Ltd|LIC Mutual Fund Ltd|LIC Pension Fund Ltd|[[IDBI Bank]]}}\n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.licindia.in/}}\n| foundation          = 1 September 1956\n| location            = [[Mumbai, India]]\n}}\n\n'''Life Insurance Corporation of India''' (abbreviated as '''LIC''') is an Indian state-owned [[insurance]] group and [[investment]] corporation owned by the [[Government of India]]. \n<br>The Life insurance Corporation of India was founded on September 1, 1956 when the [[Parliament of India]] passed the Life Insurance of India Act that nationalized the insurance industry in India.  Over 245 insurance companies and provident societies were merged to create the state-owned Life Insurance Corporation of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mylicindia.com/lic-life-insurance-corporation-of-india/|title=LIC - Life Insurance Corporation Of India|last=Anushka|website=My LIC India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"licindia.in\"/>\n\nAs of 2019, Life Insurance Corporation of India had total life fund of \u20b928.3 trillion.The total value of sold policies in the year 2018-19 is \u20b921.4 million. Life Insurance Corporation of India settled 26 million claims in 2018\u201319. It has 290 million policy holders.\n\n==History==\n[[File:LIC Zonal Office.jpg|thumb|right|LIC Zonal Office, 'Night View From Connaught Place Park']]\n\n===Founding organisations===\nThe Oriental Life Insurance Company, the first company in India offering life insurance coverage, was established in [[Kolkata]] in 1818. Its primary target market was the Europeans based in India, and it charged Indians heftier premiums.<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=http://www.licindia.in/history.htm |title=History |publisher=LIC |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216111317/http://www.licindia.in/history.htm |archivedate=16 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Surendranath Tagore]] had founded Hindustan Insurance Society, which later became Life Insurance Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/lunch-on-lotus-leaves/cid/1265929|title=Lunch on lotus leaves|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Bombay Mutual Life Assurance Society, formed in 1870, was the first native insurance provider. Other insurance companies established in the pre-independence era included\n* Postal Life Insurance (PLI) was introduced on 1 February 1884\n* Bharat Insurance Company (1896)\n* [[United India Insurance Company|United India]] (1906)\n* National Indian (1906)\n* [[National Insurance Company|National Insurance]] (1906)\n* Co-operative Assurance (1906)\n* Hindustan Co-operatives (1907)\n* Indian Mercantile\n* General Assurance\n* Swadeshi Life (later Bombay Life)\n* Sahyadri Insurance (Merged into LIC, 1986)\n\nThe first 150 years were marked mostly by turbulent economic conditions. It witnessed [[Indian rebellion of 1857|India's First War of Independence]], adverse effects of the [[World War I]] and [[World War II]] on the [[economy of India]], and in between them the period of worldwide economic crises triggered by the [[Great depression]]. The first half of the 20th century saw a heightened struggle for [[India's independence movement|India's independence]]. The aggregate effect of these events led to a high rate of and [[liquidation]] of life insurance companies in India. This had adversely affected the faith of the general in the utility of obtaining life cover.\n\n===Nationalization in 1956===\n\n[[File:The Jeevan Bharati building at Connaught Place, New Delhi.jpg|right|thumb|LIC Zonal Office, at [[Connaught Place, New Delhi]], designed by [[Charles Correa]], 1991.]]\n[[File:LIC Chennai.JPG|thumbnail|right|LIC Building at Chennai, was the tallest building in India when it was inaugurated in 1959]]\nIn 1955, parliamentarian Feroz Gandhi raised the matter of insurance fraud by owners of private insurance agencies. In the ensuing investigations, one of India's wealthiest businessmen, Ramkrishna Dalmia, owner of the ''[[Times of India]]'' newspaper, was sent to prison for two years.\n\nThe [[Parliament of India]] passed the Life Insurance of India Act on 19 June 1956 creating the Life Insurance Corporation of India, which started operating in September of that year. It consolidated the business of 245 private life insurers and other entities offering life insurance services; this consisted of 154 life insurance companies, 16 foreign companies and 75 provident companies. The nationalization of the life insurance business in India was a result of the [[Industrial Policy Resolution of 1956]], which had created a policy framework for extending state control over at least 17 sectors of the economy, including life insurance.\n\n==Structure==\nThe LIC's executive board consists of Chairman, currently M R Kumar, and Managing Directors, Vipin Anand, T. C. Suseel Kumar, Mukesh Kumar Gupta and Raj Kumar<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/mr-kumar-appointed-lic-chairman-vipin-anand-tc-sushil-kumar-named-managing-directors-3644101.html/amp |title=board structure |work=moneycontrol |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.licindia.in/Top-Links/About-Us/Board-Of-Directors |title=bod}}</ref>\n\n== LIC's Contribution to the five year plans over the years ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Plan !! Year !! Investment\n|-\n| 2 || 1956-1961 || \u20b9184 Cr\n|-\n| 3 || 1961-1966 || \u20b9285 Cr\n|-\n| 4 || 1969-1974 || \u20b91,530 Cr\n|-\n| 5 || 1974-1979 || \u20b92,942 Cr\n|-\n| 6 || 1980-1985 || \u20b97,140 Cr\n|-\n| 7 || 1985-1990 || \u20b912,969 Cr\n|-\n| 8 || 1992-1997 || \u20b956,097 Cr\n|-\n| 9 || 1997-2002 || \u20b91,70,929 Cr\n|-\n| 10 ||2002-2007 || \u20b93,94,779 Cr\n|-\n| 11 ||2007-2012 || \u20b97,04,720 Cr\n|-\n| 12 ||2012-2017 || \u20b914,23,055 Cr\n|-\n| 13 ||2017-2022 || \u20b928,01,483 Cr\n|-\n|}\n\n===Growth as a monopoly===\nFrom its creation, the Life Insurance Corporation of India, which commanded a [[monopoly]] of soliciting and selling life insurance in India, created huge surpluses and by 2006 was contributing around 7% of India's [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nThe corporation, which started its business with around 300 offices, 5.7 million policies and a [[Capital (economics)|corpus]] of INR 45.9 crores (US$92 million as per the 1959 exchange rate of roughly {{INR}}5 for US$1),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.un.org/Data.aspx?d=CDB&f=srID:6080 |title=UNdata &#124; record view &#124; Exchange rate, US$ per national currency, period average (IMF) |publisher=Data.un.org |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=30 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> had grown to 25,000 servicing around 350 million policies and a [[Capital (economics)|corpus]] of over {{INRConvert|800000|c}} by the end of the 20th century.\n\n===Liberalisation post 2000s===\nIn August 2000, the [[Indian Government]] embarked on a program to liberalise the insurance sector and opened it up for the private sector. LIC emerged as a beneficiary from this process with robust performance, albeit on a base substantially higher than the private sector.\n\nIn 2013 the first year premium [[compound annual growth rate]] (CAGR) was 24.53% while total life premium CAGR was 19.28% matching the growth of the life insurance industry and outperforming general economic growth.<ref>{{cite web|author=CA. Nirmal Ghorawat |url=http://canirmalg.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/few-perspectives-on-life-insurance-in-india/ |title=Perspectives on Life Insurance Industry in India \u00ab CA. Nirmal Ghorawat's Blog |publisher=Canirmalg.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nToday LIC functions with 2048 fully computerized branch offices, 8 zonal offices, around 113 divisional offices, 2,048 branches and 1408 satellite offices and the Central Office;<ref name=AR201112>{{cite web|url=http://www.licindia.in/Annual_Report_2012.pdf |title=Annual Report 2011-2012 |publisher=LIC |accessdate=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628044340/http://licindia.in/Annual_Report_2012.pdf |archivedate=28 June 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> it also has 54 customer zones and 25 metro-area service hubs located in different cities and towns of India. It also has a network of 1,537,064 individual agents, 342 Corporate Agents, 109 Referral Agents, 114 Brokers and 42 Banks for soliciting life insurance business from the public.\n\nNow LIC also has the 1899 branches of [[IDBI]] bank at its disposal thus it can carry out its insurance business through these branches of the bank.\n\n==Slogan==\nLIC's slogan ''yogakshemam vahamyaham'' is in [[Sanskrit]] which loosely translates into English as \"Your welfare is our responsibility\".  This is derived from ancient Hindu text, the [[Bhagavad Gita]]'s 9th chapter, 22nd .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vedabase.net/bg/9/22/en |title=Bhagavad-gita As It Is Chapter 9 Verse 22 |publisher=Vedabase.net |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023045529/http://vedabase.net/bg/9/22/en |archivedate=23 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The slogan can be seen in the logo, written in [[Devanagari]] script.\nThis line means \"I carry what they lack, and I preserve what they have\" (refers to [[Krishna]] speaking to [[Arjuna]]), when taken in context of the entire verse.\n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n* The Economic Times Brand Equity Survey 2012 rated LIC as the No. 6 Most Trusted Service Brand of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/brand-equity/most-trusted-brands-2012-top-50-service-brands/articleshow/17101285.cms |newspaper=Economic Times |title=Most Trusted Brands 2012: Top 50 Service Brands|date=7 November 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n* From the year 2006, LIC has been continuously winning the Readers' Digest Trusted brand award.\n* Voted India's Most Trusted brand in the BFSI category according to the Brand Trust Report for 4 continuous years - 2011-2014 according to the [[The Brand Trust Report|Brand Trust Report]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-01-23/news/30655455_1_brand-trust-report-trust-research-advisory-n-chandramouli|title = The Economics Times|last = |first = |date = |work = |accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==Employees and agents==\nAs on 31 March 2018, LIC had 111,979 employees, out of which 24,510 were women .\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Category of employees!! Total Number!! No. of Women\n|-\n| Class-I Officers || {{0|00}}32,803 || {{0|000}}7,041\n|-\n| Class-II Development Officers|| {{0|00}}22,830 || {{0|000}}1,148\n|-\n| Class III/IV employees || {{0|00}}64,346 || {{0|00}}16,321 \n|-\n| Total ||  {{0|0}}114000 || {{0|00}}24,510 \n|}\n\n=== Agency strength ===\n\nThe total number of Agents on our Roll is 11,48,811 as at 31.03.2018 as against 11,31,181 as on 31.03.2017. The number of Active Agents is 10,71,945 as at 31.03.2018 as compared to 10,46,484 as on 31.03.2017.<ref>[http://www.licindia.in/getattachment/Bottom-Links/annual-report/LIC-Annual-Report-2017-2018-WEB.pdf.aspx]</ref>\n\n==Initiatives==\n'''Golden Jubilee Foundation'''<br>\nLIC Golden Jubilee Foundation was established in 2006 as a charity organization. This entity has the aim of promoting education, alleviation of poverty, and providing better living conditions for the under privileged. Out of all the activities conducted by the organisation, Golden Jubilee Scholarship awards is the best known. Each year, this award is given to the meritorious students in standard XII of school education or equivalent, who wish to continue their studies and have a parental income less than {{INRConvert|100000}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licindia.in/GJF_scholarship.htm |title=Golden Jubilee Scholarship Scheme |publisher=LIC |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215095442/http://www.licindia.in/GJF_scholarship.htm |archivedate=15 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Holdings==\nLIC holds shares worth about \u20b92.33 lakh crore in all the Nifty companies put together, but it lowered its holding in a total of 27 Nifty companies during the quarter.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe cumulative value of LIC holding in these 27 companies fell by little over \u20b98,000 crore during the quarter shows the analysis of changes in their shareholding patterns.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIndividually, LIC is estimated to have sold shares worth \u20b9500-1,000 crore in each of Mahindra & Mahindra, HDFC Bank, ICICI Bank, Tata Motors, L&T, HDFC, Wipro, SBI, Maruti Suzuki, Dr Reddys and Bajaj Auto.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe insurance behemoth also trimmed holdings in Ambuja Cements, Cipla, TCS, Lupin and Asian Paints. A marginal decline was also witnessed in its stakes in companies such as IDFC, Hindustan Unilever, Grasim, ACC, BPCL, Bank of Baroda, Punjab National Bank, Sun Pharma and Tata Power.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nOn the other hand, LIC further ramped up its stake in a total of 14 Nifty constituents with purchase of shares worth an estimated \u20b94,000 crore.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe major companies where LIC has raised its stake include Infosys, RIL, Coal India Ltd and Cairn India. Other such companies are ITC, Power Grid Corp, NTPC, Siemens, Bharti Airtel and Hero MotoCorp.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe state-run insurer also marginally hiked its exposure in Ultratech, Gail India, Ranbaxy, Kotak Mahindra Bank and HCL Technologies, while its shareholding remained almost unchanged in companies like ONGC, Tata Steel, BHEL and Reliance Infra.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nAmong the Nifty companies, LIC's holding in terms of value in 2012 were estimated to be the highest in ITC (\u20b927,326 crore), followed by RIL (\u20b921,659 crore), ONGC (\u20b917,764 crore), SBI (\u20b917,058 crore), L&T (\u20b916,800 crore), and ICICI Bank (\u20b910,006 crore).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/stock-markets/lic-cuts-stake-in-27-nifty-firms-sells-shares-worth-rs-8000-crore/article20572603.ece1|title=LIC cuts stake in 27 Nifty firms; sells shares worth Rs 8,000 crore|first=|last=PTI|website=@businessline|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe share price drop in ITC on 18 July 2017 had caused LIC a major loss of around 7000 Crores.\n\nLIC now also holds 51% stake in IDBI bank thus making it the only insurer in India to own a bank, since regulations prohibit insurers from holding more than 15% stake in any company, LIC will have to decide a timeline for paring its stake in IDBI bank; also LIC will have to pare its stake in LIC Housing Finance Ltd as a company cannot be promoter of 2 finance companies carrying out same housing finance business so either LIC has to sell its stake in LIC housing or close down housing business of IDBI bank.\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nseindia.com/live_market/dynaContent/live_watch/equities_stock_watch.htm|title=NSE - National Stock Exchange of India Ltd.|website=www.nseindia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Insurance in India]]\n* [[Insurance]]\n* [[LIC Housing Finance]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<!-- Addition of unofficial, promotional or spam links in this section will be removed! -->\n<!--CID govt india under prosed tax colection! -->\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Life Insurance Corporation of India}}\n<!--Do not add unnecessary websites. Wikipedia is not a collection of links!-->\n* [http://www.licindia.in/ Life Insurance Corporation of India] - Official LIC Website\n\n{{Insurance in India}}\n{{Indian PSU}}\n{{Major insurance companies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Life Insurance Corporation Of India}}\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Government-owned insurance companies of India]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Life insurance companies of India]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Largest insurance\n company in World}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Life Insurance Corporation\n| logo                = LIC Logo.svg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| logo_caption        = ''Yogakshemam Vahamyaham ''\n| type                = [[Government-owned corporation|Statutory Corporation]] established by an <br> [[Act of Parliament]]- <br>LIC Act 1956<br />\n| key_people          = M R Kumar (Chairman) T C Suseel kumar (Managing Director) vipin Anand (Managing Director) Mukesh Gupta (Managing Director) Rajkumar (Managing Director)\n| industry            = Financial services\n| products            = {{unbulleted list |[[Life insurance]], |[[health insurance]], |[[Investment management]],|[[Banking]],|[[Mutual fund]]}}\n| revenue             = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|337000|c}}\n(2019)\n| operating_income    = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|32241|c}}\n| net_income          = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|29956|c}}\n(2019)\n| assets              = {{Increase}}{{INRConvert|3111847|c}}(2019)\n| equity              = \n| owner               = '''[[Government of India]]''' (100%)\n| num_employees       = 111,979 (Mar 2019)<ref name=\"licindia.in\">https://www.licindia.in/getattachment/Bottom-Links/annual-report/LIC-Annual-Report-2015-16.pdf.aspx</ref>\n| subsid              = {{Unbulleted list|[[LIC Housing Finance]]|LIC International Ltd|LIC Cards Services Ltd|LIC Mutual Fund Ltd|LIC Pension Fund Ltd|[[IDBI Bank]]}}\n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|http://www.licindia.in/}}\n| foundation          = 1 September 1956\n| location            = [[Mumbai, India]]\n}}\n\n'''Life Insurance Corporation of India''' (abbreviated as '''LIC''') is an Indian state-owned [[insurance]] group and [[investment]] corporation owned by the [[Government of India]]. \n<br>The Life insurance Corporation of India was founded on September 1, 1956 when the [[Parliament of India]] passed the Life Insurance of India Act that nationalized the insurance industry in India.  Over 245 insurance companies and provident societies were merged to create the state-owned Life Insurance Corporation of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mylicindia.com/lic-life-insurance-corporation-of-india/|title=LIC - Life Insurance Corporation Of India|last=Anushka|website=My LIC India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"licindia.in\"/>\n\nAs of 2019, Life Insurance Corporation of India had total life fund of \u20b928.3 trillion.The total value of sold policies in the year 2018-19 is \u20b921.4 million. Life Insurance Corporation of India settled 26 million claims in 2018-19. It has 290 million policy holders.\n\n==History==\n[[File:LIC Zonal Office.jpg|thumb|right|LIC Zonal Office, 'Night View From Connaught Place Park']]\n\n===Founding organisations===\nThe Oriental Life Insurance Company, the first company in India offering life insurance coverage, was established in [[Kolkata]] in 1818. Its primary target market was the Europeans based in India, and it charged Indians heftier premiums.<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=http://www.licindia.in/history.htm |title=History |publisher=LIC |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216111317/http://www.licindia.in/history.htm |archivedate=16 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Surendranath Tagore]] had founded Hindustan Insurance Society, which later became Life Insurance Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/lunch-on-lotus-leaves/cid/1265929|title=Lunch on lotus leaves|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Bombay Mutual Life Assurance Society, formed in 1870, was the first native insurance provider. Other insurance companies established in the pre-independence era included\n* Postal Life Insurance (PLI) was introduced on 1 February 1884\n* Bharat Insurance Company (1896)\n* [[United India Insurance Company|United India]] (1906)\n* National Indian (1906)\n* [[National Insurance Company|National Insurance]] (1906)\n* Co-operative Assurance (1906)\n* Hindustan Co-operatives (1907)\n* Indian Mercantile\n* General Assurance\n* Swadeshi Life (later Bombay Life)\n* Sahyadri Insurance (Merged into LIC, 1986)\n\nThe first 150 years were marked mostly by turbulent economic conditions. It witnessed [[Indian rebellion of 1857|India's First War of Independence]], adverse effects of the [[World War I]] and [[World War II]] on the [[economy of India]], and in between them the period of worldwide economic crises triggered by the [[Great depression]]. The first half of the 20th century saw a heightened struggle for [[India's independence movement|India's independence]]. The aggregate effect of these events led to a high rate of and [[liquidation]] of life insurance companies in India. This had adversely affected the faith of the general in the utility of obtaining life cover.\n\n===Nationalization in 1956===\n\n[[File:The Jeevan Bharati building at Connaught Place, New Delhi.jpg|right|thumb|LIC Zonal Office, at [[Connaught Place, New Delhi]], designed by [[Charles Correa]], 1991.]]\n[[File:LIC Chennai.JPG|thumbnail|right|LIC Building at Chennai, was the tallest building in India when it was inaugurated in 1959]]\nIn 1955, parliamentarian Feroz Gandhi raised the matter of insurance fraud by owners of private insurance agencies. In the ensuing investigations, one of India's wealthiest businessmen, Ramkrishna Dalmia, owner of the ''[[Times of India]]'' newspaper, was sent to prison for two years.\n\nThe [[Parliament of India]] passed the Life Insurance of India Act on 19 June 1956 creating the Life Insurance Corporation of India, which started operating in September of that year. It consolidated the business of 245 private life insurers and other entities offering life insurance services; this consisted of 154 life insurance companies, 16 foreign companies and 75 provident companies. The nationalization of the life insurance business in India was a result of the [[Industrial Policy Resolution of 1956]], which had created a policy framework for extending state control over at least 17 sectors of the economy, including life insurance.\n\n==Structure==\nThe LIC's executive board consists of Chairman, currently M R Kumar, and Managing Directors, Vipin Anand, T. C. Suseel Kumar, Mukesh Kumar Gupta and Raj Kumar<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/mr-kumar-appointed-lic-chairman-vipin-anand-tc-sushil-kumar-named-managing-directors-3644101.html/amp |title=board structure |work=moneycontrol |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.licindia.in/Top-Links/About-Us/Board-Of-Directors |title=bod}}</ref>\n\n== LIC's Contribution to the five year plans over the years ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Plan !! Year !! Investment\n|-\n| 2 || 1956-1961 || \u20b9184 Cr\n|-\n| 3 || 1961-1966 || \u20b9285 Cr\n|-\n| 4 || 1969-1974 || \u20b91,530 Cr\n|-\n| 5 || 1974-1979 || \u20b92,942 Cr\n|-\n| 6 || 1980-1985 || \u20b97,140 Cr\n|-\n| 7 || 1985-1990 || \u20b912,969 Cr\n|-\n| 8 || 1992-1997 || \u20b956,097 Cr\n|-\n| 9 || 1997-2002 || \u20b91,70,929 Cr\n|-\n| 10 ||2002-2007 || \u20b93,94,779 Cr\n|-\n| 11 ||2007-2012 || \u20b97,04,720 Cr\n|-\n| 12 ||2012-2017 || \u20b914,23,055 Cr\n|-\n| 13 ||2017-2022 || \u20b928,01,483 Cr\n|-\n|}\n\n===Growth as a monopoly===\nFrom its creation, the Life Insurance Corporation of India, which commanded a [[monopoly]] of soliciting and selling life insurance in India, created huge surpluses and by 2006 was contributing around 7% of India's [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nThe corporation, which started its business with around 300 offices, 5.7 million policies and a [[Capital (economics)|corpus]] of INR 45.9 crores (US$92 million as per the 1959 exchange rate of roughly {{INR}}5 for US$1),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.un.org/Data.aspx?d=CDB&f=srID:6080 |title=UNdata &#124; record view &#124; Exchange rate, US$ per national currency, period average (IMF) |publisher=Data.un.org |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=30 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> had grown to 25,000 servicing around 350 million policies and a [[Capital (economics)|corpus]] of over {{INRConvert|800000|c}} by the end of the 20th century.\n\n===Liberalisation post 2000s===\nIn August 2000, the [[Indian Government]] embarked on a program to liberalise the insurance sector and opened it up for the private sector. LIC emerged as a beneficiary from this process with robust performance, albeit on a base substantially higher than the private sector.\n\nIn 2013 the first year premium [[compound annual growth rate]] (CAGR) was 24.53% while total life premium CAGR was 19.28% matching the growth of the life insurance industry and outperforming general economic growth.<ref>{{cite web|author=CA. Nirmal Ghorawat |url=http://canirmalg.wordpress.com/2013/01/31/few-perspectives-on-life-insurance-in-india/ |title=Perspectives on Life Insurance Industry in India \u00ab CA. Nirmal Ghorawat's Blog |publisher=Canirmalg.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nToday LIC functions with 2048 fully computerized branch offices, 8 zonal offices, around 113 divisional offices, 2,048 branches and 1408 satellite offices and the Central Office;<ref name=AR201112>{{cite web|url=http://www.licindia.in/Annual_Report_2012.pdf |title=Annual Report 2011-2012 |publisher=LIC |accessdate=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628044340/http://licindia.in/Annual_Report_2012.pdf |archivedate=28 June 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> it also has 54 customer zones and 25 metro-area service hubs located in different cities and towns of India. It also has a network of 1,537,064 individual agents, 342 Corporate Agents, 109 Referral Agents, 114 Brokers and 42 Banks for soliciting life insurance business from the public.\n\nNow LIC also has the 1899 branches of [[IDBI]] bank at its disposal thus it can carry out its insurance business through these branches of the bank.\n\n==Slogan==\nLIC's slogan ''yogakshemam vahamyaham'' is in [[Sanskrit]] which loosely translates into English as \"Your welfare is our responsibility\".  This is derived from ancient Hindu text, the [[Bhagavad Gita]]'s 9th chapter, 22nd .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vedabase.net/bg/9/22/en |title=Bhagavad-gita As It Is Chapter 9 Verse 22 |publisher=Vedabase.net |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023045529/http://vedabase.net/bg/9/22/en |archivedate=23 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The slogan can be seen in the logo, written in [[Devanagari]] script.\nThis line means \"I carry what they lack, and I preserve what they have\" (refers to [[Krishna]] speaking to [[Arjuna]]), when taken in context of the entire verse.\n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n* The Economic Times Brand Equity Survey 2012 rated LIC as the No. 6 Most Trusted Service Brand of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/brand-equity/most-trusted-brands-2012-top-50-service-brands/articleshow/17101285.cms |newspaper=Economic Times |title=Most Trusted Brands 2012: Top 50 Service Brands|date=7 November 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n* From the year 2006, LIC has been continuously winning the Readers' Digest Trusted brand award.\n* Voted India's Most Trusted brand in the BFSI category according to the Brand Trust Report for 4 continuous years - 2011-2014 according to the [[The Brand Trust Report|Brand Trust Report]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-01-23/news/30655455_1_brand-trust-report-trust-research-advisory-n-chandramouli|title = The Economics Times|last = |first = |date = |work = |accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==Employees and agents==\nAs on 31 March 2018, LIC had 111,979 employees, out of which 24,510 were women .\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Category of employees!! Total Number!! No. of Women\n|-\n| Class-I Officers 